Looking at feature correlations.¶

If there are features too correlated with each other or with the target I will have to remove them, because they could introduce overfitting.

In [4]:
cor = df.corr()
In [5]:
sns.heatmap(cor, annot=True, cmap=plt.cm.Reds)
plt.show()

The above correlation map is too cluttered, I will manually check if there are elements higly correlated with each other.

In [6]:
correlated_features = []
theshold = 0.6
for col_name, row in cor.iterrows():
    for other in row[row > theshold].index:
        if other != col_name:
            if (other, col_name, row[other]) not in correlated_features:
                correlated_features.append((col_name, other, row[other]))

From above I can definelty see that there are few higly correlated features, hence to avoid overfitting I will delete some.

NOTE: I have actually run this correlation step quite a few time before getting to this set of features. Initally I added many more features, and after analysing the correlation I have decided to go back and eliminate few. This has been an iterative process which I have omitted for clarity.

The data is a bit unbalanced, but it is not too extreme, but would be better to do some over and under sampling.

Random Undersampling and Oversampling

In [10]:
# Divide by class
df_class_0 = df[df['target'] == 'not churned']
df_class_1 = df[df['target'] == 'churned']

df_class_0_under = df_class_0.sample(int(len(df_class_0) * 0.6)) # Reduce by 40%
resamples = df_class_1.sample(int(len(df_class_1)*0.5)) # Sample extra 50%
df = pd.concat([df_class_0_under, df_class_1, resamples], axis=0)
print('Random under-sampling:')
print(df.target.value_counts())

Random under-sampling:
not churned    37167
churned        10756
Name: target, dtype: int64
In [11]:
X = df.loc[:, df.columns != 'target']
y = df.loc[:, 'target']

Building models¶

I am going to try 3 different models: RandomForestClassifier, LogisticRegression and XGBClassifier. The first two are really for benchmark. They can give a good estimate of what can be achieved in terms of performances with little or no parameter tuning. I will then compare XGBClassifier, a more advanced classifier with the default parameters to see how it compares. I will later do some grid search to see if I can further improve its performances.

In [12]:
model_rf = RandomForestClassifier(min_samples_split=5, n_estimators=300) 
model_lr = LogisticRegression(solver='liblinear')
model_xgb = XGBClassifier(objective="binary:logistic")

Looking at Feature importance¶

Let's look at random forest feature importance

In [19]:
model_rf.fit(X, y)
feat_importances = pd.Series(model_rf.feature_importances_, index=X.columns)
ax=feat_importances.nlargest(20).plot(kind='barh')
_=ax.set_title("Most Imoportant features")
In [20]:
ax=feat_importances.nsmallest(20).plot(kind='barh')
_=ax.set_title("Least Imoportant features")

It looks like that there are some features that really do not need to be include, as the could just introduce noise. Let's try remove features that contribute less than 0.01 and let's see if performances improve.

In [21]:
ax=sns.distplot(feat_importances)
ax.axvline(0.01, c='r')
_=ax.set_title("Distribution of importance scores")

Seems that a treshold at 0.01 will cut off quite a lot of unimportant features

Error analysis¶

Let's now look at the type of errors that the best classifier produce.

In [27]:
# shuffle and split training and test sets
X_train, X_test, y_train, y_test = train_test_split(X, y, test_size=.15, random_state=3)

y_score = model_rf.fit(X_train, y_train).predict_proba(X_test)[:, 0]
y_predicted = model_rf.fit(X_train, y_train).predict(X_test)
print("F1 score: {}".format(f1_score(y_test, y_predicted, average='macro')))

# Compute ROC curve and ROC area for each class
fpr, tpr, _ = roc_curve(y_test, y_score, pos_label='churned')
roc_auc = auc(fpr, tpr)

F1 score: 0.830427545120028
In [28]:
lw = 2
plt.plot(fpr, tpr, color='darkorange',
         lw=lw, label='ROC curve (area = %0.2f)' % roc_auc)
plt.plot([0, 1], [0, 1], color='navy', lw=lw, linestyle='--')
plt.xlim([0.0, 1.0])
plt.ylim([0.0, 1.05])
plt.xlabel('False Positive Rate')
plt.ylabel('True Positive Rate')
plt.title('Receiver operating characteristic curve')
plt.legend(loc="lower right")
plt.show()
